name: Anonymous
com:
Characters are everything in a dialogue heavy animation movie for me. They can either make or break a movie. In this case, i find Astro, Tenma, Cora and Elefun to be more likeable than Hiccup, Stoick, Astrid and Gobber. This also extends to the supporting cast : AB has likeable and colorful characters like Orrin, Zog, RRF, Trashcan and Widget, whereas HTTYD has unlikeable and drab characters like Snotlout, Fishlegs and those annoying twins.

As for Stone, he's not a great villain, but still better than a huge evil dragon who only exists to serve as the final boss and who's never mentioned or referenced again after his death.

name: Anonymous
com: Whereas Astroboy has a humble, likeable and charming style of writing, HTTYD's writing feels smug, self important and too serious minded, like it wants so hard to be respected as an important classic and become a media franchise. This also extends to the soundtrack. Whereas John Ottman's pieces are epic, cheerful, optimistic and uplifting, with a tingle of innocence, John Powell's soundtrack is just epic and brooding, nothing else. It tries too hard

It's not autism, you just don't know the context. It's a parody of a meme in Korea. When Heroes of the Storm failed miserably in Korea, It became a laughing stock among online games. And when they started to release Overwatch characters on Hots(OW sucks now but it was big back then), people started a meme about old Blizz characters abducting OW characters. This meme developed into various comics/videos that seemed to be high-quality OW fanfiction with good art style and plot. But then at the climax, when readers were getting invested and off-guard, fucking portal to Hots nexus opens and kidnaps OW characters, and then it ends with low-res Hots commercial. When people began to expect such endings, memers moved onto characters and ips completely unrelated to Blizzard. And it wasn't always Hots anymore. It could be any game with a suffering player base in Korea.

I'm trying to build out from there and have something a bit more complex than the one note. I posted this last thread but I thought I'd put it here as well since it was near the end.

>PANKRASH CIRCLE FIGHTING

"An internal/external style, Pankrash Circle Fighting has gone through many iterations. One of the most notable of these is derived supposedly from the teachings of the Sword-Saint, a practitioner in his day. While the mention of swords might make one initially question an entry in this account, it deserves at least a passing mention due to its mostly unarmed nature."

The style is defensive first and foremost, and it focuses on gradually building up internal forces necessary to retaliate to an attacker with a single, channeled blow directed towards a point of weakness. This is done through continuous motion in combat with an emphasis on deflection and absorbing blows. While this seems simple to accomplish to an observer, it is much more difficult in practice.

The most unusual facet of the style is most apparent in its rarest technique. A skilled fighter can, reputedly, build up so much internal energy over the course of a battle that when he looses it, it creates a result not dissimilar to what is colloquially called "Cutting". (This is a topic expounded upon at length in an infamous sword manual written by a madwoman, so does not need further mention here.)

While this effect is typically seen only when a Pankrash Circle Fighter wields a weapon, the greatest masters are reputed to do this with their bare hands. Unfortunately, though, I have not in my travels been able to witness such an occurrence, as the style is regarded as something of an archaic oddity in this day and age."

- Manual of Hands and Feet

>>120834749
The alpha bitch isn't just some girl who dominates you. Dominating you isn't a requirement at all actually. She just needs to dominate a certain social environment. Typically in cartoons that will be a school, but could be anyplace with a variety of cliques forced to occupy the same space. The alpha bitch is the queen of the highest status clique. Her status will usually be backed up by something like money, or a highly-regarded title like cheerleading captain. That's why those show up so often.

The alpha bitch needs to have significant social influence. A hacker girl is unlikely to have this, and if she does, the hacking thing would take a back seat to playing the archetype, which is purely social in nature. The veteran girl has no social context in that scenario. Maybe if she was also the leader of the neighborhood housewives or a director at a company or something. The important components are status, influence, and being bitchy. She can be a gamer girl or whatever backstory you want, but without those components she's not an alpha bitch.

>>120823591
Now you hold the fuck on for one goddamn second, anon. The Redwall series may be written with a younger audience in mind but they are in no way "children's books" in content. For every goofy mole singing about how much they love to eat pudding there is a tense moment where the heroes have to escape from an encampment of cannibalistic frogs. For every heartwarming feast where young children play with their food while their parents watch and laugh, there is a chilling moment as we watch the main villain have nightmares and mental breakdowns incited by the guardian spirit of Redwall itself. For every weird game of hedgehogs wrestling on stilts, there is an ex-pirate strangling his captain in retaliation for years of physical abuse and destroying the only good thing he ever had.

The books have silly moments, to be sure, but the silly moments do not define the Redwall series. Redwall, at its core, is about good, brave woodland animals protecting their homes and families from the onslaught of evil beasts that try to bring them down. These books champion bravery, kindness, and loyalty above everything else, and they pull no punches in portraying what fighting for these ideals actually means.

A book that has a happy ending is not automatically something that only children can appreciate.

>>120825503
>RAW
Robert Anton Wilson is great. Combination of crazy conspiracy theories, occultism, action, absurd humor and stylistic experimentation. You wanna start with the Illuminatus trilogy. His nonfiction writing on magic is also pretty interesting although if you're interested in the occult I'd just skip straight to people like Phil Hine and Peter J. Carroll since they were covering the same ground as RAW but have a lot more practical ritual in their books.

>comic recs
Since you mention pulp fantasy, you might enjoy Scion or Sojourn from CrossGen. Scion is sci-fantasy about a wayward prince in a medieval world full of biotech and robotics and Sojourn is a generic high fantasy fetch quest.The latter has art by porn tracing era Greg Land so ymmv but I found them both very fun. Conan the Cimmerian from Dark Horse and the Black Library Warhammer Fantasy comics are also very good if you don't mind licensed stuff.

>>120832375
Utility monster is a flawed argument by stating that an increase of a resource will lead to an increase of utility as much as it did previously. In other words, you might have ten bikes instead of one, but you can only ride one bike at a time so having additional bikes, while fun for variety, is less utility giving than giving nine of those bikes to people who have no bikes.

Otherwise you take it to the logical extreme that a single person on the planet will be supremely happy when we know that isn't true. Conversely, it supports the nation that humanity gets happier the more people exist, because resources get scarcer but there is more people to have utility when they get the resource, even if it is smaller than with a lower pop

tl;dr utility monster is a meme but neat thought experiment

>>120827965
The Earth Kingdom was always a bunch of semi-independent feudal states, since it was just too big to govern any other way before mass transportation/communication. Everyone paid their dues to the king in Ba Sing Se, but otherwise ran their own affairs and were largely culturally independent. That's why Bumi could be named "king" of his city state, yet still answer to the actual Earth King. And this only gets magnified by a hundred years of warfare keeping the Earth King's forces distracted while the Dai Lee are deliberately keeping the king, and Ba Sing Se as a whole for that matter, disconnected from the rest of the kingdom.
Also keep in mind that the Earth Kingdom has had a long history of warlords and civil wars. Chin the Conquerer had taken over pretty much the whole kingdom a couple hundred years prior to Kuvira. To all the petty little feudal governors who probably never got much attention from Ba Sing Se besides taxes and who don't fully understand the ramifications of being incorporated into a network of high speed rail and telecommunications, Kuvira would just seem like another Chin.

I still think a lot of the first Avatar's strength is the fact that they knew what long-term story arc they wanted to work towards from day-one. So they could devote real time to establishing different character arcs and fleshing out different parts of the world. Korra was originally written to fit into mini-series only to be given a surprise order for more. Imagine if Zuko was written to be introduced, built up, and redeemed all in one season instead of three, and then after doing so the writers are suddenly informed that they have several more seasons to find something new to focus on.

I'm not saying Bryke had no faults in what they gave screen-time to in Korra (mainly that painful love triangle) but I feel for them in having to write around the network constantly surprising them both with orders for more episodes and orders to drop episodes.

>>120819280
Well I guess my read on the Season Two finale is that that's Rapunzel at the height of her folly.

In Season Two Raps almost has a death wish. She wants to plod on to her "destiny," no matter what it is. It very much seems like she has a desire not to be cooped up by anything, so she'll keep pushing forward, even when the likely result is her death. She gets pretty hell-bent. She wants to go forward, even after the terror of the Great Tree. Even after the House Of Yesterday's Tomorrows. Even after Demanitus warns them all that the road ahead is perilous. Even when they sing that song about how things might come to an end.

Rapunzel in Season Two comes off as having more than a little bit of a death wish. I think she wants to live until she dies, in Season Two. She wants her destiny and she'll take it, even if it kills her.

And in that regard, Cass betraying her kind of does her a favor. This is what shocks her out of her death spiral. Cassandra's betrayal makes her realize, "No, there are things I love, I love my home, I love Eugene my one true love, I don't want to leave, there are things I value." I think Cass' betrayal and taking of the Moonstone leads directly into the very gung-ho active queen Raps we see in Season 3. Cassandra's betrayal essentially snaps her out of her desire to destroy everything else in her life. Cass taking the Moonstone makes her realize how much she has in her life that's precious and valuable, and worth preserving. And as a response to this, Raps goes full mama bear in Season 3 and is determined to protect Corona at all costs, from any enemies, including the enemy of her best friend that she knows is out there.

Actually this is really interesting. I wonder if Rapunzel would actually have married Eugene, if it weren't for Cassandra's betrayal. There's a lot of fun character development and psychology at work in Rapunzel, between Season 2 and Season 3.

Ever since Eugene came crawling through her tower window, Rapunzel has had this thing where she calls out to the universe for something she wants and then blindly follows the person who "answers" it. She calls out for a chance to see the lights - Eugene answers by taking her to them. She calls out for adventure outside of her new life in the palace - Cass answers by sneaking her out to see the black rocks. She calls out for a greater purpose and the chance to "set herself free" - Adira answers by telling her that her destiny is too unite the sundrop and moonstone - at the potential cost of her own life.

In the latter two instances, she finds that the person who answered the previous call is actively standing in the way of the next one. Eugene does this by proposing to her at her coronation and expressing his desire to stay there with her in the palace forever and ever. Cass does it by vowing to protect her no matter what, even if it meant saying "fuck your destiny". In both instances, Raps takes a step back from that person. Eugene handles it with patience, trust, and maturity. Cass...does not.

Trailers have shown almost nothing of the show. Everything in the trailers is from the first episode except Madripoor and the shot of Zemo with his mask in hand from the newest trailer(which is ironically from the last episode)

Therapy sessions are a bookend for the show, every episode starts/is intercut with them. Ross is watching.

Flagsmasher is not a major character, just a side character used by Zemo as a distraction. Show in general follows a villain of the week format with the exception of Zemo who is built across the 6 episodes.

Steve Rogers does not die(at least not in this show). There is a funeral, but it's for General Ross(he's not really dead, but going underground)

John Walker is referred to as Captain America throughout his run with the shield. At one point he is referred to in dialogue as "a US Agent" but that's it. He's not a full on villain, he genuinely wants what's best for the country but he follows orders to a fault and has crippling PTSD.

Race is a HEAVY theme in the show. Sam isn't allowed the shield because of the Sokovia Accords, but the real reason is because he is black. When Walker goes off the reservation and beats Eli Bradley in front of cameras, the government tries to give Sam the shield for good PR. This almost leads Sam to forsaking the government entirely but Rhodey brings him back.

Show doesn't really set Rhodey up for Armor Wars at all.

Bucky's arc is atonement and becoming a human again in the small ways he can. Sharon helps him with this immensely.

The 5 years after the snap are explored heavily, as is the impact of coming back to a changed world.

Omega Red and Batroc the Leaper are indeed in the show. They are the villains of episode 3, which is the Madripoor episode. Omega Red is pretty nerfed for the MCU but there's a canon reason. The word "mutant" is never said.

Songbird does NOT appear. Neither do the Inhumans in any capacity. There's also no tie in to Black Widow, at least not one that I noticed.

>>120787153
It’s interesting that bratty scheming little girl who gets into antics was so common (presumably to the point it became old hat and fell out of favor) considering how it contrasts with our image of mass media at the time being squeaky-clean and moralizing and that post-“girl power” stuff it feels rare to find prominent female characters in mixed-gender shows who aren’t blandly the most grounded and competent of the cast.
We’re gradually getting more, as female MCs are the trend right now and not all of them can be milquetoast self-inserts (..right?) but regardless cartoons have still slid into an attempted “sincere” mode since the mid-2010s in which most shows neatly wrap up with a moral for the kiddos, there isn’t much of a pure anarchic comedic spirit out there in the realm of mainstream kid stuff anymore.
I’d like to see a show where a lead girl is unashamedly a little shit, though unfortunately autists who project too hard would probably hate such a character if they get away with their pranks.

com:
I tend to think about "Help I'm A Fish" occasionally.

I sometimes question myself if Joe was truly in the wrong. Sure, he was power-hungry and ruthless, but so were the leaders of the very first primal people after they've just evolved from apes. He needed those qualities to survive.

I like to ponder, what would have happened if he succeeded? If he managed to get to the surface and force the professor to make more of that serum, or even grow smart enough to make more himself, and produce an army of super intelligent fish people. That would probably be a mini-alien invasion scenario, only in this case the aliens would come from the Earth itself. The government would try to hide their existence/wipe them out/experiment on them, or all three at once. Depending on how many fish Joe could get to and how intelligent they'd become, they could potentially lead an all-out race war with humanity for the right to be the dominant biological unit on the planet.

Perhaps humanity would eventually end up victorious and the invasion of the fish people would be a very, very weird and controversial page of world history. Perhaps fish people would've won and built a society of their own, where centuries later history would remember Joe as a barbarian, but the one whose actions were necessary for the early advancement of fishkind. Or perhaps, after the war has caused heavy casualties on both sides, humans and fish people could somehow come to a compromise and agree to live in peace. And we all would have fish waifus.

This was a fun little movie when I saw it as a kid but nowadays I can't help but think that this concept of a large animal group suddenly gaining intelligence and posing a threat to humanity is so much bigger than the movie itself. And not generic shit like apes or insects, but fish, which is just so weird and unique. It's so fascinating to ponder.

Not him, and I could be very confused, but I think you can’t even have a Louis the XVI until after Louis the XV has already died.

With them, I think “Louis the number” was more like a title they claimed when they ascended to the thrown than like a straight succession of guys all literally named Louis. Kinda like how the Pope takes on a new name when he becomes the Pope.

Also, in the French Revolution, even if both Louis the XV and the XVI were alive, I’m pretty sure they would have to kill both of them anyway. A big point of the executions was ending the bloodlines and getting rid of people so that they couldn’t just come back and reclaim their titles later in case the revolution thing didn’t work out and the overthrowing got overthrown by the last guys in charge, returning everything to status quo.

>>120803356
Get a 21:9 monitor if you hate 2.35 letterboxing so much. 16x9 is the worst because it is neither close to square like 4:3 so you can fit a small grouping of people in frame well, and it's not wide enough to actually be wide and give impressive vistas, show things horizontally moving well or give an impression of speed into the frame. It's a gimped ratio that only exists as a halfway point between two actual aspect ratios.
>>120803405
>90% of 2k releases are upscales
>even 2k is less than x1000 pixels
I'll give you that much, because the retards making the bluray standard and the UHD-BD standards didn't think to have any provisions for anamorphic resolutions so you can be more flexible with the ratio and still make the most use of the disc space you do have. DVD got this right, assuming they were formatted by the DVD pressers properly, why the fuck not for BD?
Though as a side effect, if you get a 3440x1440 monitor, and watch a "4K" movie that's 2.35 or something close, you're only really shrinking the frame down a tiny bit to fit all your resolution. And it's pretty close to the 2K some productions lazily produce at anyway.

>For reasons relating to intellectual property law, and the need to preserve "Transformers" as a trademark, Hasbro and Takara do not use "transform" as a verb to describe this ability of Transformers in printed materials describing products. >For some time, this restriction didn't extend to in-fiction dialogue. However, in more recent times this has changed. James Roberts has said that Hasbro has asked that other terms be used when writing IDW comics such as More Than Meets the Eye. Exceptions have been made, though, when dialogue or drama strongly called for it, such as the NAIL who transformed himself to death. How to Say Goodbye and Mean It In Fall of Cybertron, Ratchet actually commands Bumblebee to "change form and roll out", and Optimus Prime only ordered his team to "transform and roll out" twice during the Prime cartoon, opting instead for a "roll out" for the majority of the series.

com:
OK, autism incoming.

Set it 200+ years after the end of the Great War. The war ended when Megatron stole Vector Sigma and attempted to use it to rewrite the sparks of all Transformers and convert them to Deceptions. Optimus Prime tried to stop him, but was defeated in their final battle. But while Megatron was distracted, Spike Witwicky took Vector Sigma and, with no other options, forced it to self-destruct, dying alongside Megatron in the ensuing blast.

Leaderless and shocked by the loss of Vector Sigma, the Deceptions have no choice but to sue for peace. It's a victory, but one that Optimus cannot accept. The Witwickys blame him for Spike's death, and he agrees, believing he has failed irreconcilably by his weakness in a crucial moment costing an innocent their life. He abdicates as leader of the Autobots, and gives the matrix to Hot Rod, who is not nearly ready to take over, before exiling himself to seclusion.

In the present day, the Autobots rule Cybertron. Hot Rod, now Rodimus Prime, has made the best of the role he was thrust into and has become a good leader, but is continually hamstrung by the Autobot Council, publicly elected officials who are beginning to warp the government's duties to grasp at more power. These young politicians weren't there for the war, to see how crucial humans were in aiding the Autobot cause. Now, in the modern day, as humanity begins to colonize the stars and is approaching Cybertron in levels of technological advancement, the Council is growing jealous of them and is beginning to ponder ways of curbing humanity, to Rodimus's dismay.

All of this is compounded by a resurgence of Cybertronian extremists: Predacons, a new Transformer subspecies that seems to have originated on Earth itself, bio-mechanical beings that can take on "Beast modes".

No one knows where they came from, but their volatile leader Predaking has ambition, believing his species to be the next phase in Transformer evolution, and the inheritors of the "spark of revolution" passed down to them by the Decepticons, and the spirit of Megatron. They've begun violent insurgencies across Earth, and the humans have begun to blame the Autobots, their allies, for letting it happen. But when Rodimus tries to send aid, the Council prevents him, hoping the Predacons will weaken the overly-ambitious humans and keep Cybertron ahead.

This is Rodimus's breaking point, and sensing that he's on the brink of war between human and Transformer, he draws his wildcard: Optimus. Still in seclusion on a distant world, maintaining an old records facility, Optimus is reluctant to aid his old protégé. He has grown fearful and regretful in his exile, and doubts the bot Rodimus came looking for still exists within him. But Rodimus is convincing, and reminds Optimus that it was not a Prime who stood up to Megatron all those eons ago, but a simple data clerk named Orion. And that's the bot he came to find..

name: Anonymous
com:
>>120826050
Rodimus recruits Prime as a means of circumventing the Council. He is not going to Earth to fight the Predacons, but to train a rookie team of Autobots fresh from the academy:
>Windblade, brash and overconfident, and thinks poorly of Optimus as a washed up old scrapheap. Claims to be a City-speaker, but her city has stopped responding to her. Has the makings of a leader if not for her own pride.
>Hot Shot, a wild and upbeat scout with a bad habit of hero-worshipping, especially Optimus.
>Rhinox, a "Maximal", supposedly like a Predacon but born on Cybertron. Wise beyond his years, but prone to illness due to being a secret experiment by the Council to create artificial Maximals as anti-Predacon propaganda.
>Jetfire II, named for the original and eager to live up to his namesake, despite his self-destructive aggressive flying
>And Remus Pax, a failed journalist that can transform into a video camera.

With these fresh faces, Optimus travels to Earth, where under the guise of training them they wage a battle against the Predacon uprising, attempting to discover Predaking's lair and where these Predacons are coming from.

The first season would primarily be about Optimus coming back into his own as a leader, grappling with his self-doubts, compounded by meeting the descendants of the Witwickys, who have come to mistrust all Transformers. Protecting them from the Predacons becomes a means for Optimus to atone in his own eyes for his failure to protect Spike. Subplots would include Windblade's backstory and why she lost her ability to speak to her Titan partner, and the mystery of Remus Pax, whom Predaking takes a personal interest in, culminating in a double-whammy reveal at the season finale: The true leader of the Predacons is Shockwave, who has used his science to accelerate the evolution of Predacons using the vivisected spark of Starscream as a base for the species.

name: Anonymous
com:
>>120826072
And second, when Shockwave attempts to experiment upon a captured Remus's spark, his software is corrupted by the ghost of Megatron himself, confirming Predaking's suspicion - Remus Pax is Megatron, reincarnated and without his memories.

From there further seasons would spiral out of control, as the Predacons attempt to force Megatron to revive through sacrificing Remus, while Megatron's spirit attempts to guide Remus on a new path, abandoning both Autobot and Decepticon alike. Meanwhile, even as rogue human elements prepare to spark a war with Cybertron and Team Prime desperately attempts to help their human allies root them out, Cybertron itself comes under siege as a new sect of Predacons rises up, seemingly independent of Shockwave's and led by someone who claims to be Megatron reborn, yes...

All new Peanuts aficionados should begin to read the strip in its entirety. It's completely worth it, and will give you much needed insight into the motivations of characters when you move into the animated content (which doesn't compare in that regard).
All Peanuts strips are available on the Peanuts wiki in chronological order:
>https://peanuts.fandom.com/wiki/October_1950_comic_strips

Either while you're reading the strips or afterwards, you can watch all of the specials + original movies + The Charlie Brown and Snoopy Show using the Internet Archive. I recommend as you go through the strip, by date released for the most authentic experience.
>https://archive.org/details/PeanutsCharlieBrown/Charlie+Brown+-+A+Charlie+Brown+Christmas.avi

All information on order of release by date is found on the Peanuts wiki:
>https://peanuts.fandom.com/wiki/Peanuts_Wiki

All of this should be done before you even THINK about watching the Snoopy Show, as it is littered with references and Easter Eggs towards more knowledgeable fans that a newfriend simply wouldn't pick up on.

I, like most Peanuts fans I think, regard Race For Your Life as being a mostly bad special. With that being said though there are moments I really enjoy. Charlie Brown filling into that general leadership role is a nice moment and honestly pretty fitting for him characteristically, given his actions on the baseball field.

I also genuinely enjoy the scenes in which the kids are stranded in the mountains, there's a lot of funny interactions involved in that. Charlie telling off Peppermint Patty is a direct reference to the Thanksgiving Special (as seen in >>120774070 post), serving to show just how much his character has changed because he filled in this leadership role among the boys. Peppermint Patty quite likes Charlie's assertiveness, too, she very happily eats her cereal after getting told off by him. It has quite a bit of cute moments like this.

With that being said, I'd absolutely agree that the film would be much better if the main antagonists were taken out entirely.

Essentially, yeah. The show is honestly really great and serves Peanuts really well. The comedy is pretty good, the writing is surprisingly friendly to the lore, with many anons ITT pointing out highlights such as >>120774580 . There are some minor quirks like Peppermint Patty/Marcie going to the same school as the other kids, but that was the same in the Peanuts movie. The fact that they pulled off something like this telling what is basically totally original stories. It could be a bit more melancholy but that can’t be helped.

I’ll definitely be waiting in anticipation for a second season and am as shocked as you are about it. I’d recommend this show to any Peanuts fan.

>>120791029
An important thing you’re missing is that these characters ARE Sparky. They are direct mirrors of himself and his life experiences. Rerun was expanded upon as a character once Schulz had his first grandkid, which marked a significant change in his life despite his age. Lucy’s changes and development are in direct result of this. This is expanded upon in a lot of Schulz history books, where Lucy is said to “take a more motherly role to Rerun” instead of being a big sister like she is to Linus. It’s the readers job to correlate these characters with real world scenarios and situations that can be relatable to anyone, it’s what Schulz’s goal was. Something happens to Schulz, something happens to Charlie Brown and the gang.

>>120791029
First off:
>Please show me the point where I said that the characters never changed on purpose.
>None of them had canonical reasons to act different

Secondly, don't use falsehoods such as Lucy supposedly being based on Schulz's wife (even if, for whatever reason, you don't believe it yourself...?). By doing so you perpetuate myth. On a substance level, its basically equal to the "theory" that Peppermint Patty and Marcie were secretly written to be lesbians.

Lastly and most importantly, what you're pushing back against is, at its very basic level, the practice of literary analysis and the verifiable fact that Schulz's comics had depth not spoken directly. There are many examples of further depth in Peanuts.

For the purpose of explanation I'll use a very popular concept often mentioned in these threads: Peppermint Patty's veritably strong relationship with her father and her subsequent love for Charlie Brown. There are many specific strips that while obviously not directly saying as much, imply an acute mental association between Peppermint Patty's father and her love for Charlie Brown. She will mention her father to Charlie constantly, these interactions (often posted here) make an association between the two men in her life blindingly obvious. Just a couple examples of this are the flowers Patty receives from her dad that she presents to Charlie Brown (October 4th 1970) and Patty informing Charlie Brown of her father-given nickname as a "rare-gem." When Charlie agrees with this moniker she's very happy about it and falls deeper in love with him (October 4th 1971).

If you want a direct example of Schulz making this mental connection Peppermint Patty has between her father and Chuck so abundantly clear that a reader could come to no other conclusion, just look at pic related (June 20, 1976).

This franchise is too great to be forced into creative stagnation for a cause that doesn't even make sense in the first place.

First off, I'll admit to being biased because I'm one of the very few people who's favorite /co/ characters have always been the FF. I think they are all great characters, and that they have to be a team for the most interesting bits of characterisation to come through.

Reed being a piece of shit gets brought up a lot. But think of it from his perspective. If there's four walls and a ceiling, he's the smartest man in the room. He's kind of it for human science heroes, he's where it stops. If there's a problem and he can't solve it, everyone else is pretty much boned. Imagine having as much knowledge of alternate realities and potential futures as he does. He's seen humanity die a thousand ways, and he knows that every time represents his personal failure. That's why we get things like the Thor clone and the various superweapons he's got lying around. Reeds entire life is dedicated to advancing the cause of humanity, but the only thing that keeps him human is his family. Also he's actually kind of a great dad, to some of the hardest kids imaginable to raise.

Then there's Johnny. He's kind of a dick, and he knows it. He shows off a lot and can't always back it up. But that's mostly a cover for some serious self esteem issues. He's the weakest member of the team, and he knows that too. His brother in law can build a spaceship with rubber bands and paperclips. His sister is a thousand times more mature and successful, and is far happier. His best friend literally has rocks for a dick, and has a stable relationship, and a bigger fanclub. He's the little brother, who's now approaching his thirties and hasn't made anything of himself without his family's support. Despite all that, he's still dedicated to doing the right thing when he can. Him becoming a firefighter is one of the neatest ideas that never got used properly.

One thing that bugs me, is how the relationship between him and Ben is presented outside of the comics. They hated each other, but that was years ago. They still give each other shit, but there's mutual respect there that holds absolutely true.

It was a Stark bomb, with the words "STARK" on it in big letters. She had to listen to that ticking bomb for two days. That would give anyone PTSD. Despite that pain she attended Stark's funeral and paid respects to him.

Wanda was deliberately provoked by some assholes, a bunch of evil witches, and possibly up to three extra-dimensional shitlords.

I have a problem with the show's depiction of dark magic, personally. When I was first told about the show I imagined that dark magic would revolve around killing sentient magic things and grinding them into spell juice. But that's not universally the case at all since regular dumb animals or even bugs can be the catalysts for spells.
Who of you wouldn't slit a deer's throat if it meant healing your quadriplegic brother? How is that evil? The only thing the show seems to say is that it's bad because the spells have serious recoil on the user. Again how is that bad?
If you could could burn down a tree and bring back your father from the dead, but you would cripple yourself in the process, is that evil? The vast majority of cultures' archetypal heroes celebrate self sacrifice. This show would tell me that's bad. Good luck flying in the face of thousands of years worth of culture on that count.

I really, really think the show has to unfuck its moralizing around dark magic. Yes it had aborting a dragon egg portrayed as a bad thing. Yes it had turning your army into half zombie fire Wights being a bad thing. Those things aren't self sacrifice though and they're actually touching sentients. Which is again, what I thought the moral quandary would actually be about.

Their heights are exaggerated to better convey the feel of being young with an impossible crush on someone older. In real life there are lots of adult women who are shorter than teen boys but without the budget or art direction to add in subtle detailing to the character designs it’s easier to portray age being represented by height.

com: The concept behind the "guy" character is a double reverse psy-op with the purpose of diluting the topic of modern cartoons rapidly stagnating approach to design with broken-record style posting that echoes "anti-bean mouth" sentiment popularized on this board some odd years ago, but boiled down to it's most derivative form - this wide-spread spam approach serves to aggravate and annoy onlookers to the point of quashing any of their preconceived notions / predilections on the matter, and sicken them of this endemic mode of discourse so much that they resign altogether from engaging in it due to just how cartoonishly overplayed and trite it has become. There is nothing wrong with desiring a more thoughtful approach to cartooning- but beanmouth spam, clear to all, is not a fruitful way to go about it. In reality, "guy" is either one or more people that wish to subvert the narrative of reactionary cartoon rhetoric to the point that the opposite of the standard becomes so reviled that the standard is even more ingratiated than it already is, insofar that at the very least, the predominately "lazy" modern "beanmouth" approach to design is more tolerated, as to defy it in anyway is to be, in some capacity, comparable in spiritual essence to the much maligned "guy" character, and no one wants to be like the "guy" character - he is engineered to be ill-tempered, embarrassing, likes Homestuck - once this threshold is reached, any critique of the modern commonplace approach to cartooning becomes one in the same, and all equally repugnant. At this, theories on who is behind the "guy" character can be extracted - those that play the "guy" character very well may be the "shills" that "guy" posts so often about, potentially even industry professionals that wish to keep the efficient and relatively cheap standards of animation exactly as they are by removing any possibility of opposition at its roots. It's a sly approach, but wasted cause no one gives a shit anymore anyways.
